Most infections produce few or no symptoms . Acute symptoms include variable fever , lymphadenopathy , malaise , and hepatosplenomegaly . The entry site may be inflamed for up to 8 weeks , and a diagnostic unilateral bipalpebral edema -LRB- Romana 's sign -RRB- appears in a few cases . After a latent period which may last 10 -- 30 years , chronic irreversible sequelae occur in 20 -- 30 % of cases : myocardial lesions with arrhythmia , often fatal , andlesions of the esophagus , colon , and peripheral nervous system . Variations in clinical presentations can be related to the strain involved . Group I T. cruzi , rare north of the Amazon region , produce cardiac but not digestive tract lesions . Group IIT . cruzi can produce both cardiac and digestive tract lesions . AIDS patients may develop meningoencephalopathy . CFR from encephalomyelitis or cardiac failure among untreated symptomatic patients is 5 -- 10 % .
During urban epidemics , biting midges -LRB- Culicoides paraensis -RRB- ; also mosquitoes of Aedes and Culex genera .
